WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.255
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.050 --> 00:00:09.320
MATT BRITTIN: So please welcome,
enthusiastically and warmly,

00:00:09.320 --> 00:00:09.960
Viv Groskop.

00:00:09.960 --> 00:00:13.446
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:15.438 --> 00:00:16.434
VIV GROSKOP: Thank you.

00:00:16.434 --> 00:00:17.430
Hey.

00:00:17.430 --> 00:00:18.426
Thank you, Matt.

00:00:18.426 --> 00:00:18.924
MATT BRITTIN: Thank
you very much.

00:00:18.924 --> 00:00:20.418
VIV GROSKOP: Thank you.

00:00:20.418 --> 00:00:23.910
Oh, in the spirit
of Google Translate,

00:00:23.910 --> 00:00:25.905
I feel like I should
say [RUSSIAN]..

00:00:28.647 --> 00:00:30.480
MATT BRITTIN: Well,
that's very rude of you.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:32.647
VIV GROSKOP: There any
Russian speakers in the room?

00:00:32.647 --> 00:00:34.380
Yeah.

00:00:34.380 --> 00:00:34.920
So--

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:35.970
MATT BRITTIN: What
did you say there?

00:00:35.970 --> 00:00:36.420
VIV GROSKOP: Hello.

00:00:36.420 --> 00:00:36.840
Thank you.

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:37.340
I love you.

00:00:37.340 --> 00:00:38.903
MATT BRITTIN: Oh.

00:00:38.903 --> 00:00:41.070
I can see this is going to
be a great chat with you.

00:00:41.070 --> 00:00:42.810
VIV GROSKOP: Yeah.

00:00:42.810 --> 00:00:45.300
MATT BRITTIN: Let's just
start with-- what do you mean,

00:00:45.300 --> 00:00:46.300
owning the room?

00:00:46.300 --> 00:00:47.790
What does that mean?

00:00:47.790 --> 00:00:50.550
VIV GROSKOP: Well, you just
demonstrated it, actually,

00:00:50.550 --> 00:00:53.280
with that little
slip-up that you had,

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:56.550
not being able to
say Anna Karenina.

00:00:56.550 --> 00:00:59.150
So can you say it now?

00:00:59.150 --> 00:01:01.665
MATT BRITTIN: No.

00:01:01.665 --> 00:01:03.540
VIV GROSKOP: Owning the
room is about feeling

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:07.200
really comfortable in the
spotlight, so comfortable

00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:08.970
that you're OK with failing.

00:01:08.970 --> 00:01:11.010
That's it, basically.

00:01:11.010 --> 00:01:13.500
Because in everyday
life, when we're

00:01:13.500 --> 00:01:16.360
talking to people, when we're
just moving through our lives,

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:18.660
we don't go around
thinking, oh, I'm

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:20.430
going to meet my
friend with coffee--

00:01:20.430 --> 00:01:23.010
for coffee-- but I haven't
prepared anything to say.

00:01:23.010 --> 00:01:25.680
You know, we move through
life very comfortably,

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:27.390
and we don't question ourselves.

00:01:27.390 --> 00:01:30.090
But suddenly, when we're
in a position like--

00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:32.160
not literally like
this, but sometimes,

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:34.680
literally like this-- where
we're in a spotlight--

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:37.440
but that spotlight can
feel like it comes anytime,

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.410
like in an interview
situation, job interview,

00:01:40.410 --> 00:01:44.010
in a difficult conversation with
your boss, in a confrontation.

00:01:44.010 --> 00:01:46.980
We can feel like we're
in that spotlight.

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:49.955
And that is the moment
when the adrenaline comes,

00:01:49.955 --> 00:01:51.580
and we have that
fight or flight, which

00:01:51.580 --> 00:01:54.630
is very natural human reaction.

00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:57.520
It's about learning how to
be comfortable with that,

00:01:57.520 --> 00:02:01.170
control it, and feel like you're
just owning yourself in the way

00:02:01.170 --> 00:02:04.110
that you do in normal moments.

00:02:04.110 --> 00:02:06.870
I've gotten quite Paul
McKenna quite early on.

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:08.400
That's OK.

00:02:08.400 --> 00:02:11.790
MATT BRITTIN: So we're
going to go into, I think--

00:02:11.790 --> 00:02:13.290
get practical about
what you learned

00:02:13.290 --> 00:02:14.748
and what you've
shared in the book.

00:02:14.748 --> 00:02:16.980
But before we do that, I
mentioned this idea of doing

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:18.870
a hundred stand-up
gigs in a hundred days,

00:02:18.870 --> 00:02:22.780
which you did when you had
a child under one, I think--

00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:23.618
VIV GROSKOP: Yes.

00:02:23.618 --> 00:02:25.660
MATT BRITTIN: --as If it
wasn't stressful enough.

00:02:25.660 --> 00:02:27.120
Just tell us a bit
about, like, why

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:28.582
did you do-- why
did you do that?

00:02:28.582 --> 00:02:30.540
VIV GROSKOP: Well, some
people will do anything

00:02:30.540 --> 00:02:34.410
to avoid bedtime
for small children,

00:02:34.410 --> 00:02:36.510
and I was one of those people.

00:02:36.510 --> 00:02:39.090
And what happened to me
was that, as you said,

00:02:39.090 --> 00:02:41.910
I had a long and
very happy career

00:02:41.910 --> 00:02:44.190
as a freelance journalist.

00:02:44.190 --> 00:02:46.860
I started my career
in my early 20s,

00:02:46.860 --> 00:02:49.233
working in old-school
Fleet Street, which

00:02:49.233 --> 00:02:51.150
lots of the beautiful
young people in the room

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:53.220
won't even remember.

00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:56.953
So I had a office job
until I was about 25,

00:02:56.953 --> 00:02:59.370
working for places like "The
Daily Express" and "The Daily

00:02:59.370 --> 00:03:01.540
Telegraph," and places I hated.

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:04.140
And that was a good experience
for me to be in a job I hated.

00:03:04.140 --> 00:03:06.140
It made me go freelance.

00:03:06.140 --> 00:03:09.600
And then I had about 10 years of
loving writing and freelancing.

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:11.863
And that was how I was able
to have my three children.

00:03:11.863 --> 00:03:14.280
I have three children, which
is an answer to the question,

00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:17.100
how many children is too many.

00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:20.340
And as I go into my mid 30s--

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:22.560
and I felt like I had a lot
of control over my life,

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:24.440
because I had a
lot of flexibility.

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:26.230
And I loved my work--

00:03:26.230 --> 00:03:28.650
I began to realize that, as
my children were growing up,

00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:30.270
I was telling them a lie.

00:03:30.270 --> 00:03:31.980
So I was always
saying to them, do

00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:33.390
what you want with your life.

00:03:33.390 --> 00:03:34.410
Live your dreams.

00:03:34.410 --> 00:03:36.810
Don't let other people
tell you what to do.

00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:38.280
And the more I
said this to them,

00:03:38.280 --> 00:03:40.810
the more I realized
it wasn't true for me,

00:03:40.810 --> 00:03:43.240
and that the thing I'd
always wanted to do,

00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:46.150
which was to perform,
to entertain,

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:50.370
to be in the spotlight-- to
really try stand-up comedy was

00:03:50.370 --> 00:03:51.900
what I really wanted to do--

00:03:51.900 --> 00:03:53.010
I'd never done it.

00:03:53.010 --> 00:03:54.797
Because I was too damn chicken.

00:03:54.797 --> 00:03:55.380
I was chicken.

00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:58.230
MATT BRITTIN: How did you know
that's what you wanted to do?

00:03:58.230 --> 00:04:02.160
VIV GROSKOP: I had had an
idea from when I was a child.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:05.010
People-- and again,
too young to remember--

00:04:05.010 --> 00:04:07.000
the kids from "Fame"--

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:07.500
yeah?

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:08.370
1980s?

00:04:08.370 --> 00:04:09.090
AUDIENCE: Yeah!

00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:11.010
Yeah.

00:04:11.010 --> 00:04:12.810
VIV GROSKOP: Doris Schwartz--

00:04:12.810 --> 00:04:14.660
Doris Schwartz and
Bruno Martelli,

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:16.387
and the kids from
"Fame," Mr. Shorofsky--

00:04:16.387 --> 00:04:17.720
MATT BRITTIN: Yeah, [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:18.887
VIV GROSKOP: You were there.

00:04:18.887 --> 00:04:20.250
MATT BRITTIN: I was there.

00:04:20.250 --> 00:04:21.769
Still got the leg warmers, yeah.

00:04:21.769 --> 00:04:24.480
VIV GROSKOP: Doris Schwartz
was this character in this

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:29.190
mid-'80s, a woman stand-up
in the New York High School

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:30.990
of the Performing Arts.

00:04:30.990 --> 00:04:33.800
And New Yorkers in
the room cringing.

00:04:33.800 --> 00:04:36.540
And I loved her
when I was a child.

00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:38.400
But I grew up in the
kind of environment

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:40.740
where my parents
later turned out

00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:45.780
to be massive Brexit voters,
and like, quite sort of closed,

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:48.780
don't take any risks,
do not do anything

00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:50.120
creative sort of environment.

00:04:50.120 --> 00:04:51.480
So I was never--

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:53.590
I didn't feel I was able
to set that as a goal.

00:04:53.590 --> 00:04:54.840
Like, I'd love to do stand-up.

00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:55.830
I'd love to do acting.

00:04:55.830 --> 00:04:57.460
If I could live my
life over again,

00:04:57.460 --> 00:04:59.550
I would have done that
from a much younger age.

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:01.680
But instead, I kind of was
like, OK, well, maybe I

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:03.410
can be a writer.

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:05.490
And just through seeing
my own kids grow up

00:05:05.490 --> 00:05:08.970
and realizing that life is too
short to stifle the stuff you

00:05:08.970 --> 00:05:12.510
really want to do, I had to
acknowledge, yeah, actually,

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:14.460
I'm kind of hiding
behind this keyboard.

00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:16.240
I'm hiding behind the words.

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:19.300
And I've got to get out
there and at least try.

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:23.080
And so I ended up doing some
workshops and all that kind

00:05:23.080 --> 00:05:25.750
of stuff that you do
when you first try it,

00:05:25.750 --> 00:05:28.180
and realizing that I loved it.

00:05:28.180 --> 00:05:31.330
After the first workshop I ever
did in stand-up comedy when I

00:05:31.330 --> 00:05:32.020
was 35--

00:05:32.020 --> 00:05:32.980
I'm 45 now.

00:05:32.980 --> 00:05:34.450
I know, it's amazing.

00:05:34.450 --> 00:05:36.160
And I came home.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:38.680
And my husband said
to me, after doing

00:05:38.680 --> 00:05:40.970
three hours of this
stand-up training,

00:05:40.970 --> 00:05:44.260
this is the most relaxed
I've seen you in 10 years.

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:47.440
And I knew I really
wanted to do it.

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:49.300
But then you learn
very quickly how hard

00:05:49.300 --> 00:05:51.593
it is to actually do
it, and that if you

00:05:51.593 --> 00:05:53.260
are going to do it
seriously, you better

00:05:53.260 --> 00:05:55.490
get to a hundred gigs fast.

00:05:55.490 --> 00:05:58.412
And I just had my third
child, and he'd turned one.

00:05:58.412 --> 00:05:59.870
When he turned one,
I was like, OK,

00:05:59.870 --> 00:06:01.537
you've had enough
attention from me now.

00:06:01.537 --> 00:06:04.070
I'm going out every night,
a hundred gigs in a hundred

00:06:04.070 --> 00:06:04.570
nights.

00:06:04.570 --> 00:06:06.130
And that was in 2011.

00:06:06.130 --> 00:06:10.600
And since then, I've gone on
to do five shows at Edinburgh,

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:14.030
one-woman shows, and ended
up hosting book tours

00:06:14.030 --> 00:06:17.440
for Graham Norton, Dawn French,
Jennifer Saunders, Jay Brand,

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:19.870
and moving into more
radio and TV work, which

00:06:19.870 --> 00:06:21.410
is what I really wanted to do.

00:06:21.410 --> 00:06:23.260
MATT BRITTIN: So it was a route
to something else in the end?

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:24.343
VIV GROSKOP: Yeah, it was.

00:06:24.343 --> 00:06:26.927
And I would-- if you'd have
said to me, 10 years ago,

00:06:26.927 --> 00:06:28.510
oh, you're going to
be doing stand-up,

00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:32.140
and you're going to go on
stage with Graham Norton,

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:33.770
or any of these
people, and then you're

00:06:33.770 --> 00:06:37.060
going to write a book for people
about how to own the room,

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:38.590
I would be like, no, thanks.

00:06:38.590 --> 00:06:41.650
No, I don't really want--
that sounds horrible.

00:06:41.650 --> 00:06:46.480
But as time went on, I realized
how much I'd learnt about all

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:48.910
of this, and that I really
wanted to pass it on to other

00:06:48.910 --> 00:06:51.670
people, and have this
discussion about--

00:06:51.670 --> 00:06:53.827
it's not an entirely
gendered discussion,

00:06:53.827 --> 00:06:55.660
and that's a really
important point to make.

00:06:55.660 --> 00:06:58.150
But I do think it's harder,
sometimes, for women

00:06:58.150 --> 00:06:59.260
to try these things.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:03.150
And that's obviously a
huge conversation in comedy

00:07:03.150 --> 00:07:04.780
is, why aren't
there as many women?

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:06.800
I think loads more women
are coming through now.

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:09.070
And the last 10 years has
seen a massive change.

00:07:09.070 --> 00:07:11.490
But the numbers are
always really skewed.

00:07:11.490 --> 00:07:13.840
And on the comedy
bill, you're often

00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:16.180
the only woman out of six.

00:07:16.180 --> 00:07:18.790
And you're generally going to
be the opener, like, the lowest

00:07:18.790 --> 00:07:22.610
status spot, all that stuff.

00:07:22.610 --> 00:07:26.720
So having learnt how to do
this on the fly late in life,

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:28.300
I wanted to pass it on.

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:29.800
And then I found
I was constantly

00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:32.260
thinking, for the idea for
this book, and for the podcast,

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:36.700
where I interview lots of
women about all of this stuff--

00:07:36.700 --> 00:07:38.380
I was thinking, I
can't write that.

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:40.750
Because who will listen to me?

00:07:40.750 --> 00:07:43.660
I can't-- I'm not famous.

00:07:43.660 --> 00:07:45.820
No one knew-- I'm not
a massively successful

00:07:45.820 --> 00:07:46.645
stand-up comedian.

00:07:46.645 --> 00:07:48.520
And I remember saying
to this friend of mine,

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:51.190
who is a writer, I
can't write this book.

00:07:51.190 --> 00:07:54.290
This book should be
written by Joan Rivers.

00:07:54.290 --> 00:07:56.950
Like, Joan-- who would
want to read "How to Own

00:07:56.950 --> 00:07:58.030
the Room" by Joan Rivers?

00:07:58.030 --> 00:08:01.400
I mean, that would be the
most amazing book ever.

00:08:01.400 --> 00:08:03.550
And my friend just looked
at me and said, Viv,

00:08:03.550 --> 00:08:04.960
Joan Rivers is dead.

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:08.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:08.230 --> 00:08:11.200
And if she were
alive, she would not

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:13.600
be bothered to write this book.

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:15.640
She is not a book-writing
kind of person,

00:08:15.640 --> 00:08:16.790
although she did
write a lot of books.

00:08:16.790 --> 00:08:18.623
But she would not wanted
to write this book.

00:08:18.623 --> 00:08:19.810
So this is your book.

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:20.920
This is your idea.

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:23.890
Put it out there and see
if people are interested.

00:08:23.890 --> 00:08:25.930
And the book came
out in November.

00:08:25.930 --> 00:08:29.140
I met you shortly
after it came out.

00:08:29.140 --> 00:08:31.900
And it's become a bestseller.

00:08:31.900 --> 00:08:33.860
It's sold in three countries.

00:08:33.860 --> 00:08:35.919
It's coming out in
Canada next week.

00:08:35.919 --> 00:08:38.590
The podcast has gone
top 10 on iTunes.

00:08:38.590 --> 00:08:40.669
Which, the podcast got
put together in two weeks,

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:41.169
literally.

00:08:41.169 --> 00:08:45.230
Because Mary Portas, the retail
guru, came to me and said,

00:08:45.230 --> 00:08:46.810
how can I help you
with your book?

00:08:46.810 --> 00:08:49.220
And I said, well, it's
coming out in two weeks.

00:08:49.220 --> 00:08:52.540
So I can't interview
you for it or anything.

00:08:52.540 --> 00:08:56.020
How about I interview you
for the podcast, which

00:08:56.020 --> 00:08:57.940
doesn't actually
exist, but it will

00:08:57.940 --> 00:08:59.980
if you say yes to an interview?

00:08:59.980 --> 00:09:01.210
And she said yes.

00:09:01.210 --> 00:09:02.980
And so then, suddenly,
I had a podcast,

00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:04.660
which happened in two weeks.

00:09:04.660 --> 00:09:05.860
So--

00:09:05.860 --> 00:09:07.390
MATT BRITTIN: You are a woman on
a mission, though, aren't you,

00:09:07.390 --> 00:09:08.200
really?

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:11.420
VIV GROSKOP: Yeah, because
this stuff is really important.

00:09:11.420 --> 00:09:14.883
And I've been really--

00:09:14.883 --> 00:09:17.300
I've had a lot of moments of
being really upset, actually,

00:09:17.300 --> 00:09:19.630
of what I-- the stories that
have come out from doing

00:09:19.630 --> 00:09:21.490
these kind of events.

00:09:21.490 --> 00:09:23.570
I do one-on-one
work with people.

00:09:23.570 --> 00:09:26.560
I do workshops where people can
come and have a clinic with me

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:27.520
for 10 minutes.

00:09:27.520 --> 00:09:31.120
And I do little interventions
about presentation

00:09:31.120 --> 00:09:34.930
and confidence, and
men as well as women.

00:09:34.930 --> 00:09:36.910
But often, from
women-- like, the depth

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:43.090
of people's insecurity and the
weight that they're carrying

00:09:43.090 --> 00:09:47.080
with them about, my
voice sounds weird,

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:49.180
no one wants to
listen to my voice,

00:09:49.180 --> 00:09:51.528
I've got an annoying voice--

00:09:51.528 --> 00:09:53.320
I feel like I'm talking
about myself here--

00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:57.190
and all of these tiny,
little, niggling gremlins

00:09:57.190 --> 00:10:00.820
are so prevalent in everybody.

00:10:00.820 --> 00:10:02.860
And there's got to be a
way to talk about this

00:10:02.860 --> 00:10:03.910
and get rid of it.

00:10:03.910 --> 00:10:06.460
Because everybody thinks
it's personal to them,

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:08.440
and they have this
specific problem that they

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:09.940
would need some help with.

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:10.990
And it's not.

00:10:10.990 --> 00:10:12.100
Everybody has it.

00:10:12.100 --> 00:10:13.142
MATT BRITTIN: Absolutely.

00:10:13.142 --> 00:10:14.450
So I want to get into the book.

00:10:14.450 --> 00:10:16.200
So one of the things
I love about the book

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:19.630
is it's written in
chapters around people.

00:10:19.630 --> 00:10:24.472
And so "Be More Michelle
Obama" is the first chapter.

00:10:24.472 --> 00:10:25.180
VIV GROSKOP: Yes.

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:25.972
MATT BRITTIN: And--

00:10:25.972 --> 00:10:28.108
VIV GROSKOP: Demonstrate
it now, Matt.

00:10:28.108 --> 00:10:31.594
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:32.895 --> 00:10:34.828
MATT BRITTIN: I'm doing it.

00:10:34.828 --> 00:10:35.370
I'm doing it.

00:10:35.370 --> 00:10:36.620
VIV GROSKOP: You actually are.

00:10:36.620 --> 00:10:37.330
You actually are.

00:10:37.330 --> 00:10:39.510
MATT BRITTIN: So I said,
to Viv, actually, I--

00:10:39.510 --> 00:10:42.242
that chapter is about something
