00:11:18.650 --> 00:11:20.500
MATT BRITTIN: But
happy high status--

00:11:20.500 --> 00:11:20.880
VIV GROSKOP: Yeah.

00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:21.690
MATT BRITTIN: --that
is a great concept.

00:11:21.690 --> 00:11:22.690
Tell us about that.

00:11:22.690 --> 00:11:24.107
VIV GROSKOP: Yeah,
so when I first

00:11:24.107 --> 00:11:26.310
started training in
stand-up, and taking

00:11:26.310 --> 00:11:28.290
all of these workshops,
and trying to work out

00:11:28.290 --> 00:11:31.840
how I was going to
start doing this stuff,

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:34.980
I came across this
idea in improv comedy

00:11:34.980 --> 00:11:37.360
called happy high status.

00:11:37.360 --> 00:11:42.870
And it's about the
moment where you

00:11:42.870 --> 00:11:46.200
are so open and
comfortable in a space

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:48.870
that you can accept
disagreement.

00:11:48.870 --> 00:11:50.670
You can accept dissent.

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:52.650
You can accept that the
person coming after you

00:11:52.650 --> 00:11:54.030
is going to trash you.

00:11:54.030 --> 00:11:56.250
You can take on haters
and be like, yeah,

00:11:56.250 --> 00:11:58.320
tell me more about
why you hate me,

00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:00.720
and be very open and
collegiate with it,

00:12:00.720 --> 00:12:06.150
and allow everybody's viewpoints
to exist at any one time.

00:12:06.150 --> 00:12:07.800
I am personally not
very good at this,

00:12:07.800 --> 00:12:10.110
because I'm quite neurotic.

00:12:10.110 --> 00:12:12.780
But it's an energy
that you need to have,

00:12:12.780 --> 00:12:15.480
for example, if you're
MCing in comedy,

00:12:15.480 --> 00:12:18.120
where you might have to
switch the energy from one

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:19.048
comedian to the next.

00:12:19.048 --> 00:12:21.090
You might have to bring
up the energy in the room

00:12:21.090 --> 00:12:24.090
or calm it down if
somebody was really crazy.

00:12:24.090 --> 00:12:27.330
And it's about being able to
feel your way into situations

00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:29.960
where you make sure
everybody feels unthreatened

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:31.860
and everybody feels welcome.

00:12:31.860 --> 00:12:34.720
And Michelle Obama is
the expert of this.

00:12:34.720 --> 00:12:35.940
But the other example--

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:37.600
to show it's not
gendered as well,

00:12:37.600 --> 00:12:39.615
the other example
is George Clooney.

00:12:39.615 --> 00:12:40.740
MATT BRITTIN: Tell us the--

00:12:40.740 --> 00:12:41.440
tell us the story.

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:43.273
VIV GROSKOP: So the
story they use in improv

00:12:43.273 --> 00:12:45.880
about George Clooney, it's
supposed to be a made-up story.

00:12:45.880 --> 00:12:47.820
But I like to think
it's true and that it's

00:12:47.820 --> 00:12:49.290
going to happen to me one day.

00:12:49.290 --> 00:12:54.210
So you imagine that you are
going to a Hollywood party.

00:12:54.210 --> 00:12:56.550
It's the Oscars, and you're
going to the "Vanity Fair"

00:12:56.550 --> 00:12:59.380
party, which was recently
discredited by "The New York

00:12:59.380 --> 00:12:59.880
Times."

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:02.260
But imagine it's
still in its heyday.

00:13:02.260 --> 00:13:04.020
And you're going to
this fabulous party.

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:05.580
Everybody's in black tie.

00:13:05.580 --> 00:13:06.150
You're late.

00:13:06.150 --> 00:13:08.400
Your meeting your friends,
who you really want to see.

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:10.530
On the way in, you tap
a waiter on the shoulder

00:13:10.530 --> 00:13:12.300
to ask for a drink,
because you're late,

00:13:12.300 --> 00:13:13.285
and you're in a hurry.

00:13:13.285 --> 00:13:15.180
Oh, can you just get me a drink?

00:13:15.180 --> 00:13:16.398
You go and join your friends.

00:13:16.398 --> 00:13:17.940
The waiter comes
over with the drink.

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:18.870
You turn around.

00:13:18.870 --> 00:13:20.790
It's George Clooney.

00:13:20.790 --> 00:13:24.210
And you mistook George
Clooney for a waiter,

00:13:24.210 --> 00:13:27.170
which, in a black tie
situation could happen, right?

00:13:27.170 --> 00:13:28.720
Matt, you move in these circles.

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:29.220
This--

00:13:29.220 --> 00:13:30.090
MATT BRITTIN: I've done it--

00:13:30.090 --> 00:13:30.910
I've done it twice.

00:13:30.910 --> 00:13:31.702
VIV GROSKOP: Right.

00:13:31.702 --> 00:13:34.620
MATT BRITTIN: Don't do it
twice, that's all I'd say.

00:13:34.620 --> 00:13:36.510
VIV GROSKOP: And the
happy high status lesson

00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:39.730
is that George Clooney hands
you a cocktail, or your glass

00:13:39.730 --> 00:13:42.060
of champagne, or whatever,
without making you

00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:45.540
remotely feel small,
because he's George Clooney,

00:13:45.540 --> 00:13:47.460
and he can.

00:13:47.460 --> 00:13:49.080
And Michelle Obama
could do that.

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:50.340
Barack Obama could do that.

00:13:50.340 --> 00:13:52.507
They're not going to turn
around and say, excuse me,

00:13:52.507 --> 00:13:54.060
I'm not a cocktail waiter.

00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:56.520
But to show you that
happy high status is not

00:13:56.520 --> 00:14:00.030
the same as high status,
the person you could not

00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:03.070
do that with is Donald Trump.

00:14:03.070 --> 00:14:07.420
So it's not about conferred
status or a business card.

00:14:07.420 --> 00:14:09.300
It's not about the
actual position

00:14:09.300 --> 00:14:11.680
that you occupy
in the hierarchy.

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:15.708
It's about how you conduct
yourself with other people.

00:14:15.708 --> 00:14:17.500
MATT BRITTIN: I think
it's a great concept.

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:19.260
Thank you for sharing that.

00:14:19.260 --> 00:14:20.920
You mentioned Joan Ridges--

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:21.600
Rivers.

00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:22.920
She's in your book as well--

00:14:22.920 --> 00:14:24.072
"Be More Joan Rivers."

00:14:24.072 --> 00:14:24.780
VIV GROSKOP: Yeah

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:27.155
MATT BRITTIN: What do we do
when we want to be more Joan?

00:14:27.155 --> 00:14:28.920
VIV GROSKOP: Oh my
god, well, I was--

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:33.570
it was tricky including Joan
Rivers in this, actually,

00:14:33.570 --> 00:14:36.360
particularly because she's an
example of somebody, I think,

00:14:36.360 --> 00:14:40.200
whose comedy would not exist
anymore nowadays, because woke,

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:41.970
she ain't.

00:14:41.970 --> 00:14:47.190
So I wanted to include her
as an example of a person who

00:14:47.190 --> 00:14:51.720
is everything we're told, men
and women, we shouldn't be.

00:14:51.720 --> 00:14:53.980
So we shouldn't talk too fast.

00:14:53.980 --> 00:14:56.760
We must make sure that we
speak in a measured way.

00:14:56.760 --> 00:14:58.710
We must-- lots of
women are always

00:14:58.710 --> 00:15:02.700
saying, should I lower my tone
so that people can hear-- no.

00:15:02.700 --> 00:15:05.160
No, just speak like
a normal person.

00:15:05.160 --> 00:15:07.760
And Joan Rivers breaks
a lot of these rules.

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:10.320
OK, she can, because
she's a stand-up comedian.

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:13.500
But she's a person who
speaks way too fast, who

00:15:13.500 --> 00:15:15.420
has way too much energy.

00:15:15.420 --> 00:15:17.460
You can barely sort
of keep up with what

00:15:17.460 --> 00:15:19.170
she's saying supposedly.

00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:22.240
And yet you never
miss a single word.

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:24.570
So I wanted to include
lots of examples,

00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:27.000
in the book, of women
who break the rules.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.340
Because there's a lot
of these kind of fake,

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:32.270
bullshit rules around
speaking, and presenting,

00:15:32.270 --> 00:15:35.660
and how we come across to people
that-- we all know, in reality,

00:15:35.660 --> 00:15:38.780
we all have, even within our
day-to-day lives in work, like,

00:15:38.780 --> 00:15:40.610
managers who--

00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:43.330
they're not a
stereotypical manager.

00:15:43.330 --> 00:15:45.620
They are actually, maybe,
a bit more introverted

00:15:45.620 --> 00:15:47.180
than you would expect.

00:15:47.180 --> 00:15:48.680
Or they're somebody
who's a bit more

00:15:48.680 --> 00:15:50.687
relaxed in a corporate
culture than you.

00:15:50.687 --> 00:15:52.520
There are always people
who break the rules.

00:15:52.520 --> 00:15:55.550
And for me, it's really
important to try and find

00:15:55.550 --> 00:15:57.920
your own energy
and your own style

00:15:57.920 --> 00:15:59.580
by looking at those
people and saying,

00:15:59.580 --> 00:16:03.140
oh, that's not orthodox, how
are they getting away with that?

00:16:03.140 --> 00:16:04.623
That's really interesting to me.

00:16:04.623 --> 00:16:06.290
MATT BRITTIN: So we're
working on trying

00:16:06.290 --> 00:16:09.050
to get a workshop
lined up so people

00:16:09.050 --> 00:16:11.810
can experience this in
