00:16:11.810 --> 00:16:14.480
So look out for dates on that.

00:16:14.480 --> 00:16:16.760
But what do you
most often find when

00:16:16.760 --> 00:16:18.050
you're working with people?

00:16:18.050 --> 00:16:20.292
Is there's something that's
a really common issue

00:16:20.292 --> 00:16:22.250
that you have to encourage
people to deal with?

00:16:22.250 --> 00:16:25.307
Or has everybody got their
own different challenges?

00:16:25.307 --> 00:16:27.140
VIV GROSKOP: There's
one very specific thing

00:16:27.140 --> 00:16:30.230
I want to mention, because I've
noticed you doing it, Matt.

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:31.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:35.450
So it's really interesting.

00:16:35.450 --> 00:16:38.480
We had lunch in
your lovely canteen

00:16:38.480 --> 00:16:40.040
before we came on stage.

00:16:40.040 --> 00:16:42.200
And you were talking--

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:43.195
he's really worried.

00:16:43.195 --> 00:16:43.820
No, you're not.

00:16:43.820 --> 00:16:45.195
Because you're
happy high status,

00:16:45.195 --> 00:16:47.530
so you're not worried about
what I'm going to say or do.

00:16:47.530 --> 00:16:48.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:48.030 --> 00:16:48.680
So you're OK.

00:16:48.680 --> 00:16:49.305
You're OK.

00:16:49.305 --> 00:16:50.180
MATT BRITTIN: OK, OK.

00:16:50.180 --> 00:16:52.910
VIV GROSKOP: So we were
talking in a group of about 10

00:16:52.910 --> 00:16:57.080
of us, in an informal
conversational situation.

00:16:57.080 --> 00:16:59.630
And you, and lots
of other people

00:16:59.630 --> 00:17:02.880
in the group, and probably me
as well, when we're talking,

00:17:02.880 --> 00:17:04.550
we tend to talk
like this, and say

00:17:04.550 --> 00:17:06.829
what's been going on in
our week, and everything

00:17:06.829 --> 00:17:08.974
that we say goes up at
the end of every sentence.

00:17:08.974 --> 00:17:10.849
And I was really interested
because I noticed

00:17:10.849 --> 00:17:13.050
you were doing it as well.

00:17:13.050 --> 00:17:15.470
And I often say, oh,
this is something

00:17:15.470 --> 00:17:19.099
that's very common to
women and younger women.

00:17:19.099 --> 00:17:21.319
And I was very
interested to notice

00:17:21.319 --> 00:17:26.510
that you followed that
inflection as well, which

00:17:26.510 --> 00:17:30.050
is totally useful
and appropriate

00:17:30.050 --> 00:17:32.520
in a conversational setting.

00:17:32.520 --> 00:17:35.540
However, lots of
people then transfer

00:17:35.540 --> 00:17:40.730
that into a formal interview
presentation situation,

00:17:40.730 --> 00:17:44.060
and it makes everything you
say sound like a suggestion,

00:17:44.060 --> 00:17:45.890
and it weakens your power.

00:17:45.890 --> 00:17:50.032
And it's the one thing that
everybody needs to work on.

00:17:50.032 --> 00:17:52.490
Because if I stop talking to
you like (RAISING PITCH) this,

00:17:52.490 --> 00:17:54.720
you don't know if I really
mean what I'm (RAISING PITCH)

00:17:54.720 --> 00:17:55.220
saying.

00:17:55.220 --> 00:17:56.750
And last weekend,
I went to Paris,

00:17:56.750 --> 00:17:58.542
and my husband named
(RAISING PITCH) Simon.

00:17:58.542 --> 00:18:01.880
Did I even know my husband's
(RAISING PITCH) name?

00:18:04.730 --> 00:18:06.200
And it's really
interesting to me

00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:08.390
that you were talking like that.

00:18:08.390 --> 00:18:11.810
Because this kind of
talking is actually

00:18:11.810 --> 00:18:16.460
necessary for forging
bonds and for showing this

00:18:16.460 --> 00:18:18.090
isn't a formal situation.

00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:19.400
We're having a normal chat.

00:18:19.400 --> 00:18:20.480
This is day to day.

00:18:20.480 --> 00:18:22.790
But the moments where
you are in the spotlight,

00:18:22.790 --> 00:18:27.740
and you want to step up and
be heard, move out of that,

00:18:27.740 --> 00:18:29.870
"hey we're just hanging
out in the canteen

00:18:29.870 --> 00:18:32.895
and having some laska."

00:18:32.895 --> 00:18:34.240
It was quite a nice laksa.

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:34.880
MATT BRITTIN: It
was a fun lunch.

00:18:34.880 --> 00:18:35.410
VIV GROSKOP: It was a good one.

00:18:35.410 --> 00:18:36.350
It was a fun lunch.

00:18:36.350 --> 00:18:37.250
So it's--

00:18:37.250 --> 00:18:38.810
MATT BRITTIN: We shouldn't have
